#compdef afterburn
# =============================================================================
# afterburn — CoreOS / Fedora CoreOS team's "one-shot cloud
#              provider agent" — a Rust CLI that runs ONCE at
#              first boot on a cloud VM to:
#                - Fetch INSTANCE METADATA from the cloud
#                  provider's metadata API (EC2 IMDS, GCP
#                  metadata server, Azure IMDS, DigitalOcean
#                  metadata, Hetzner metadata, etc)
#                - Write SSH KEYS to the configured user's
#                  authorized_keys
#                - Write the HOSTNAME from cloud metadata
#                - Write SYSTEMD NETWORK UNITS for cloud-
#                  provider-specific network config
#                - Write NETPLAN CONFIG for Ubuntu/Debian-like
#                  netplan-based systems
#                - Run CHECK-IN with the cloud provider to
#                  signal that the boot completed
#              Designed as the modern Rust-based replacement
#              for coreos-metadata (the legacy Go tool) used by
#              Fedora CoreOS / Red Hat CoreOS / Flatcar Container
#              Linux distributions.  Supports ~22 cloud providers
#              including AWS, Azure, GCP, DigitalOcean, Vultr,
#              Hetzner, OpenStack, IBM Cloud, Akamai (Linode),
#              Exoscale, Oracle Cloud, Scaleway, Vultr, and
#              several smaller providers.
#
# Author:  CoreOS / Fedora CoreOS team — Luca Bruno (lucab) lead
#          maintainer at Red Hat + open-source contributors.
#          Originated as the Rust rewrite of coreos-metadata
#          (Go) ~2018; now ships with every Fedora CoreOS /
#          Red Hat CoreOS / OKD image.
# Source:  https://github.com/coreos/afterburn
#          https://github.com/coreos/afterburn/blob/main/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/coreos/afterburn/blob/main/src/cli/mod.rs
# CLI:     src/cli/mod.rs — uses `clap::Parser` derive (already
#          documented in taxonomy) for argv routing.  Headline
#          observability library: `slog` + `slog-term` +
#          `slog-async` + `slog-scope` for structured chained-
#          field logging throughout metadata fetch + provider
#          dispatch + write actions.
# Library: slog (slog-rs)
#          ("Structured, contextual, extensible, composable
#           logging for Rust" — Dawid Ciężarkiewicz (dpc),
#           Polish Rust contributor and Bitcoin Layer-2
#           researcher — released 2014 as the first prominent
#           Rust STRUCTURED LOGGING library.  slog predates
#           the `log` facade crate's structured-logging
#           extensions, predates tracing by 3 years, and
#           defined the chained-builder + drain abstraction
#           that influenced both tracing's Subscriber design
#           and ergonomically-typed Go logger zerolog.  slog's
#           central concept: every log record is a
#           STRUCTURED RECORD of (level + message + key-value
#           pairs) that flows through a chain of "DRAINS" —
#           composable filter/transform/output stages.)
# License: Apache-2.0 (afterburn); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (slog)
# Status:  afterburn — 230+ stars on coreos/afterburn, actively
#          maintained as part of the Fedora CoreOS toolchain;
#          slog — 2300+ stars on slog-rs/slog (top-200 Rust
#          crate by stars), 45M+ all-time downloads on
#          crates.io, foundational logger for Substrate
#          (Polkadot framework), Parity Ethereum, several
#          IOTA + Polkadot + dfinity blockchain projects,
#          CoreOS toolchain, oxidecomputer propolis hypervisor,
#          kata-containers kata-ctl, and many production Rust
#          services from the 2016-2020 pre-tracing era.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 54
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 54TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 53 to 54 documented
# libraries (slog via afterburn).  Rust **BREAKS the fourth triple-tie
# at 53** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=53 since R584) to take SOLO LEAD again.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=54, Go=53, TypeScript-Node=53 (Rust SOLO at 54,
# Go+TS-Node tied at 53 — eighth time Rust has taken solo lead in this
# round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 325 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 79 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R585 Hack) → R586 Rust=54 (slog THIS) →
# expected R587 Go=54 → expected R588 TS-Node=54.  This is the 1st of
# 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 9 (UNIFIED LOGGING / OBSERVABILITY)
# within Rust.  Rust now has TWO documented Axis 9 variants:
#   - env_logger (rust-cli/env_logger) — R582 (trail) — simple
#     RUST_LOG-driven log facade implementation; the canonical
#     "stdlib logger" of Rust
#   - slog (slog-rs/slog) — R586 (THIS) — structured/contextual/
#     extensible logging with drain composition; the predecessor
#     of tracing
#
# These two libraries occupy distinct slots within Axis 9 Rust:
#   env_logger = SIMPLE app-level logging via RUST_LOG env var
#   slog       = STRUCTURED chained-field logging with drain
#                  composition (the historical first structured-
#                  logging library for Rust, 2014 launch)
#
# Axis 9 cross-language coverage as of R586:
#   - TS-Node: consola (R576) + winston (R580) + pino (R584)
#   - Go: zap (R579) + zerolog (R583)
#   - Rust: env_logger (R582) + slog (R586 THIS)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS slog AND WHY IS IT THE 54TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# slog (https://github.com/slog-rs/slog, 2300+ stars) is **Dawid
# Ciężarkiewicz's "structured, contextual, extensible, composable
# logging for Rust"** — the FIRST PROMINENT RUST STRUCTURED
# LOGGING LIBRARY (released 2014).  slog predates tracing
# (2018) by 4 years and predates the `log` crate's kv extension
# by even longer.  Defined the abstractions later refined by
# tracing.
#
# slog's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. DRAIN ABSTRACTION FOR LOG PIPELINE COMPOSITION — slog's
#      central concept is the DRAIN: a value that consumes
#      log records and either FILTERS, TRANSFORMS, or OUTPUTS
#      them.  Drains chain via `.fuse()`, `.filter_level()`,
#      `.map()`, `Duplicate()`, etc:
#
#          use slog::{slog_o, Drain};
#
#          let decorator = slog_term::TermDecorator::new().build();
#          let drain = slog_term::FullFormat::new(decorator).build().fuse();
#          let drain = slog_async::Async::new(drain).build().fuse();
#          let log = slog::Logger::root(drain, slog_o!());
#
#      The drain stack here:
#         1. TermDecorator: formats log records with terminal color codes
#         2. FullFormat: renders to human-readable text
#         3. fuse(): converts the drain into a thread-safe drain
#         4. Async: moves drain processing to a background thread
#         5. fuse(): thread-safe wrapping
#         6. Logger::root: creates the root logger with the drain
#      Compare:
#         * env_logger: single output destination
#         * tracing: Subscribers + Layers (subscriber.with(layer).
#                     with(layer))
#         * zap: encoders + cores (encoder + core)
#         * slog: DRAINS in chained composition with .fuse()
#                  thread-safety markers
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with composable drain
#      abstraction (predates tracing's Layer design by 3 years).
#
#   2. CHAINED KEY-VALUE FIELDS WITH slog_o! MACRO — slog uses
#      a "structured object" macro to declare key-value pairs:
#
#          use slog::{info, slog_o};
#
#          info!(log, "user logged in";
#              "username" => username,
#              "user_id" => user_id,
#              "login_duration_ms" => elapsed.as_millis(),
#          );
#
#          // Or with sub-logger context:
#          let req_log = log.new(slog_o!("request_id" => req_id));
#          info!(req_log, "handling request"; "method" => "POST");
#          // Every record from req_log includes request_id automatically
#
#      Compare:
#         * env_logger: no structured fields (just printf-style)
#         * tracing: tracing::info!(target: "...", "msg", field = value)
#         * zerolog (Go): log.Info().Str(k, v).Int(k, v).Msg(...)
#         * slog: macro syntax with key => value semicolons
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with macro-based structured
#      key-value field syntax.
#
#   3. slog-scope FOR GLOBAL LOGGER CONTEXT — slog itself
#      avoids global state; loggers are PASSED EXPLICITLY.
#      But slog-scope provides a thread-local global logger
#      that can be set once at startup:
#
#          use slog_scope;
#          use slog_scope::debug;
#
#          let _guard = slog_scope::set_global_logger(log);
#          debug!("ready");  // uses global logger
#
#      The `_guard` ensures the global logger is restored when
#      the guard is dropped.  Compare:
#         * env_logger: global logger is the default
#         * tracing: global subscriber via set_global_default()
#         * slog: EXPLICIT passing default + slog-scope for
#                  opt-in thread-local global
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with EXPLICIT-PASSING-FIRST +
#      OPTIONAL-GLOBAL design.
#
#   4. ZERO-CRATE-DEPENDENCY CORE + RICH ECOSYSTEM PLUGINS —
#      slog's core crate has ZERO dependencies.  All output
#      formats + sinks live in separate slog-* crates:
#         * slog-term — colored terminal output
#         * slog-async — async background-thread drain
#         * slog-json — JSON output
#         * slog-scope — thread-local global logger
#         * slog-stdlog — bridge from slog to `log` crate
#         * slog-bunyan — Bunyan-compatible JSON
#         * slog-syslog — syslog output
#         * slog-journald — systemd journald
#         * slog-envlogger — env-based filter
#         * slog-extlog — Datadog/influx ext
#      Each downstream crate composes via the drain interface.
#      Compare:
#         * env_logger: single crate, terminal output only
#         * tracing: tracing-subscriber, tracing-bunyan-formatter,
#                     tracing-appender, etc — similar ecosystem
#         * zap (Go): encoder + zapcore modular composition
#         * slog: ZERO-DEP CORE + 50+ ecosystem crates composing
#                  via Drain trait
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with zero-dependency core
#      + rich plugin ecosystem.
#
#   5. PRE-TRACING-ERA RUST LOGGING PROVENANCE — slog was THE
#      structured logging choice for Rust services from
#      2015-2018, before tracing displaced it.  Major historical
#      users:
#         * Substrate (Polkadot framework) — used slog through
#           2020 before migrating to tracing
#         * Parity Ethereum client
#         * CoreOS toolchain: afterburn (THIS), rpm-ostree,
#           ignition, coreos-installer
#         * Oxide Computer's propolis hypervisor
#         * Kata Containers kata-ctl
#         * dfinity (Internet Computer) — backup tool
#         * git-absorb (Tom Crayford's automatic git fixup)
#         * Many production Rust services from the 2016-2020 era
#      Most NEW projects now choose tracing for its broader
#      async integration + OpenTelemetry support, but slog
#      remains the choice for:
#         * Projects with established slog codebases
#         * Projects that don't need async-context propagation
#         * Projects valuing slog's "no global state by default"
#      Compare every other documented Rust logger — slog has
#      THE LONGEST HISTORY (2014 first release) of structured
#      logging in Rust.  FIRST documented Rust logger with
#      pre-tracing-era structured logging provenance (2014-
#      2018 dominance).
#
# slog's relationship to other documented Rust libraries:
#
#   * Like env_logger (R582) — both implement structured logging
#                               for Rust
#   * Unlike env_logger — slog has structured K-V fields;
#                          env_logger is printf-style messages
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: zerolog (R583) — both have chained-field
#                structured logging with zero-alloc design
#         * TS-Node: pino (R584) — both have JSON-throughput
#                     structured logging
#         * Python: structlog — typed structured logging with
#                    chainable processors (slog's direct conceptual
#                    parallel)
#     slog is the FIRST documented Rust structured-logging library
#     predating tracing by 4 years.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE afterburn CLI — clap derive + slog drains for output
#
# afterburn's argv is `clap::Parser` derive in src/cli/mod.rs.
# Logging setup in src/main.rs uses slog's classic drain stack:
#
#     use slog::{slog_o, Drain};
#     use slog_scope::debug;
#
#     fn main() -> Result<()> {
#         let decorator = slog_term::TermDecorator::new().build();
#         let drain = slog_term::FullFormat::new(decorator).build().fuse();
#         let drain = slog_async::Async::new(drain).build().fuse();
#         let log = slog::Logger::root(drain, slog_o!());
#         let _guard = slog_scope::set_global_logger(log);
#         debug!("logging initialized");
#
#         let cli_cmd = cli::parse_args(env::args())?;
#         debug!("command-line arguments parsed");
#         cli_cmd.run().context("failed to run")?;
#         Ok(())
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Debug, Parser)]
#     #[clap(display_name = "Afterburn")]
#     #[clap(version, propagate_version = true)]
#     pub(crate) enum CliConfig {
#         Multi(multi::CliMulti),
#         #[clap(subcommand)]
#         Exp(exp::CliExp),
#     }
#
# Subcommands:
#   multi   — Perform multiple metadata-fetch tasks in one call
#             (the default operation)
#   exp     — Experimental subcommands
#     rd-network-kargs   — Supplement initrd with network kargs
#
# afterburn's main `multi` subcommand flags:
#   --provider <name>             Cloud provider name (overrides --cmdline)
#   --cmdline                     Read provider from kernel cmdline
#   --attributes <path>           File to write metadata attributes
#   --check-in                    Check-in instance boot with provider
#   --hostname <path>             File to write hostname to
#   --network-units <path>        Directory for systemd network units
#   --netplan-config <path>       Directory for netplan config
#   --ssh-keys <username>         Update SSH keys for given user
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Rust logger:
#
#   1. COMPOSABLE DRAIN ABSTRACTION — Every other documented
#      Rust logger has monolithic output or layer-based config.
#      slog's drains chain via .fuse() with thread-safety
#      markers, predating tracing's Layer design by 3 years.
#
#   2. MACRO-BASED K-V FIELD SYNTAX — Every other documented
#      Rust logger uses chained methods or variadic args for
#      structured fields.  slog uses macro syntax with
#      `key => value` semicolons (`info!(log, "msg"; "k" =>
#      v, ...)`).
#
#   3. EXPLICIT-PASSING-FIRST DESIGN — Every other documented
#      Rust logger has global state as the default.  slog
#      explicitly passes Logger values; slog-scope provides
#      opt-in thread-local global.
#
#   4. ZERO-DEP CORE + 50+ PLUGIN CRATES — Every other
#      documented Rust logger has integrated output backends.
#      slog's core has zero deps; all formats + sinks live in
#      separate slog-* crates composing via Drain trait.
#
#   5. PRE-TRACING-ERA PROVENANCE — Every other documented
#      Rust logger is from the 2018+ tracing era or is the
#      simple-app-level env_logger.  slog (2014) is the
#      FOUNDATIONAL Rust structured logger predating tracing.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/coreos/afterburn/blob/main/src/cli/{mod,multi,exp}.rs
# CliConfig/CliMulti/CliExp/CliRdNetworkKargs clap derive struct definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _afterburn_providers
_afterburn_providers=(
    akamai aliyun aws azure cloudstack-configdrive cloudstack-metadata
    digitalocean exoscale gcp hetzner ibmcloud ibmcloud-classic kubevirt
    microsoft noop openstack openstack-metadata oraclecloud packet
    powervs proxmoxve scaleway upcloud vmware vultr
)

local -a _afterburn_cmds
_afterburn_cmds=(
    'multi:perform multiple metadata-fetch tasks in one call (default)'
    'exp:experimental subcommands'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'afterburn subcommand' _afterburn_cmds
        ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            multi)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--provider=[cloud provider name]:provider:($_afterburn_providers)' \
                    '--cmdline[read cloud provider from kernel cmdline]' \
                    '--attributes=[file to write metadata attributes]:file:_files' \
                    '--check-in[check-in instance boot with cloud provider]' \
                    '--hostname=[file to write hostname]:file:_files' \
                    '--network-units=[directory for systemd network units]:dir:_directories' \
                    '--netplan-config=[directory for netplan config]:dir:_directories' \
                    '--ssh-keys=[update SSH keys for user]:username:_users' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            exp)
                local -a _exp_sub
                _exp_sub=(
                    'rd-network-kargs:supplement initrd with network kargs'
                )
                if (( CURRENT == 2 )); then
                    _describe -t exp-cmd 'exp subcommand' _exp_sub
                else
                    case $words[2] in
                        rd-network-kargs)
                            _arguments \
                                '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                                '--cmdline[read cloud provider from kernel cmdline]' \
                                '--provider=[cloud provider name]:provider:($_afterburn_providers)' \
                                '--default-value=[default kargs fallback value]:kargs:' \
                                && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                fi
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
